Q3. More fun with shell

  1. You and your friend just have finished reading Pride and Prejudice by Jane Austen. Among the four main characters in the book, Elizabeth, Jane, Lydia, and Darcy, your friend thinks that Darcy was the most mentioned. You, however, are certain it was Elizabeth. Obtain the full text of the novel from http://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/42671/pg42671.txt and save to your local folder.

    curl http://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/42671/pg42671.txt > pride_and_prejudice.txt

    Do not put this text file pride_and_prejudice.txt in Git. Using a for loop, how would you tabulate the number of times each of the four characters is mentioned?

Solution:

names="Elizabeth Jane Lydia Darcy"
for name in $names
do 
  echo $name
  grep -o -i $name pride_and_prejudice.txt | wc -l
  echo
done
## Elizabeth
## 634
## 
## Jane
## 294
## 
## Lydia
## 171
## 
## Darcy
## 418

  1. Whats the difference between the following two commands?

    echo 'hello, world' > test1.txt

    and

    echo 'hello, world' >> test2.txt

Solution: If test1.txt does not exist, the first command would create a file that would contain hello, world. If test1.txt1 already exists, the command would overwrite that file with a file that contains hello, world in it.

If test2.txt does not exist, the second command would create a file that would contain hello, world. If test2.txt already exists, the second command would add hello, world to the end of that file.

  1. Using your favorite text editor (e.g., vi), type the following and save the file as middle.sh:

    #!/bin/sh
# Select lines from the middle of a file.
# Usage: bash middle.sh filename end_line num_lines
head -n "$2" "$1" | tail -n "$3"

    Using chmod make the file executable by the owner, and run

    ./middle.sh pride_and_prejudice.txt 20 5

    Explain the output. Explain the meaning of "$1", "$2", and "$3" in this shell script. Why do we need the first line of the shell script?

Solution:

./middle.sh pride_and_prejudice.txt 20 5
## 
## Author: Jane Austen
## 
## Editor: R. W. (Robert William) Chapman
##

The outputs last line is Line 20, and there are a total of five lines (Lines 16-20).

The meaning of "$1", "$2", and "$3" in the shell script represents the order of the arguments in the command ./middle.sh pride_and_prejudice.txt 20 5.

For example, in head -n "$2" "$1", the "$1" refers to pride_and_prejudice.txt and "$2" refers to 20, so the head command shows the first 20 lines in the pride_and_prejudice.txt. file. That is piped into the tail command, and the "$3" refers to the 5, which means it only displays the last five lines (Lines 16-20).

We need the first line of the shell script because it executes the following command lines as shell.

Q4. R Batch Run

In class we discussed using R to organize simulation studies.

  1. Expand the runSim.R script to include arguments seed (random seed), n (sample size), dist (distribution) and rep (number of simulation replicates). When dist="gaussian", generate data from standard normal; when dist="t1", generate data from t-distribution with degree of freedom 1 (same as Cauchy distribution); when dist="t5", generate data from t-distribution with degree of freedom 5. Calling runSim.R will (1) set random seed according to argument seed, (2) generate data according to argument dist, (3) compute the primed-indexed average estimator and the classical sample average estimator for each simulation replicate, (4) report the average mean squared error (MSE) \[ \frac{\sum_{r=1}^{\text{rep}} (\widehat \mu_r - \mu_{\text{true}})^2}{\text{rep}} \] for both methods.

Solution:

cat runSim.R
## ## parsing command arguments
## for (arg in commandArgs(TRUE)) {
##   eval(parse(text=arg))
## }
## 
## ## check if a given integer is prime
## isPrime = function(n) {
##   if (n <= 3) {
##     return (TRUE)
##   }
##   if (any((n %% 2:floor(sqrt(n))) == 0)) {
##     return (FALSE)
##   }
##   return (TRUE)
## }
## 
## ## estimate mean only using observation with prime indices
## estMeanPrimes = function(x) {
##   n = length(x)
##   ind = sapply(1:n, isPrime)
##   return (mean(x[ind]))
## }
## 
## # set seed for random number generation
## set.seed(seed)
## 
## mseSampAvg = 0
## msePrimeAvg = 0
## for (r in 1:rep) {
##   # parse the distribution information
##   if (dist == "gaussian") {
##     # simulate data
##     x = rnorm(n)
##   } else if (dist == "t1") {
##     x = rt(n, df = 1)
##   } else if (dist == "t5") {
##     x = rt(n, df = 5)
##   } else {
##     stop("unrecognized distribution")
##   }
##   # try two methods
##   mseSampAvg = mseSampAvg + mean(x)^2
##   msePrimeAvg = msePrimeAvg + estMeanPrimes(x)^2
## }
## 
## print(mseSampAvg / rep)
## print(msePrimeAvg / rep)
## 
## # estimate mean
## estMeanPrimes(x)

gaussian <- list.files(path = "/home/tonylim/biostat-203b-2020-winter/hw1", 
                      pattern = "gauss*", 
                      full.names = FALSE)

t1 <- list.files(path = "/home/tonylim/biostat-203b-2020-winter/hw1", 
                      pattern = "t1_*", 
                      full.names = FALSE)

t5 <- list.files(path = "/home/tonylim/biostat-203b-2020-winter/hw1", 
                      pattern = "t5_*", 
                      full.names = FALSE)

gaussian <- ldply(gaussian, 
                  read.table, 
                  sep = "\t", 
                  fill = TRUE, 
                  header = FALSE, 
                  col.names = "Gaussian", 
                  stringsAsFactors = FALSE) %>%
  dplyr::filter(row_number() %% 3 != 0)

t1 <- ldply(t1, 
            read.table, 
            sep = "\t", 
            fill = TRUE, 
            header = FALSE, 
            col.names = "t1", 
            stringsAsFactors = FALSE) %>%
  dplyr::filter(row_number() %% 3 != 0)

t5 <- ldply(t5, 
            read.table, 
            sep = "\t", 
            fill = TRUE, 
            header = FALSE, 
            col.names = "t5", 
            stringsAsFactors = FALSE) %>%
  dplyr::filter(row_number() %% 3 != 0)

combined <- cbind.data.frame(gaussian, t5, t1)

add_column(combined, 
           n = c("100", "100", "200", "200", "300", 
                 "300", "400", "400", "500", "500"), 
           Method = c("PrimeAvg", "SampAvg", "PrimeAvg", "SampAvg", "PrimeAvg", 
                      "SampAvg", "PrimeAvg", "SampAvg", "PrimeAvg", "SampAvg"), 
           .before = 1)
